00:14:24,251 --> 00:14:25,052
Did anyone play that?

245
00:14:26,653 --> 00:14:28,034
Yeah?

246
00:14:28,114 --> 00:14:30,415
We made Majesty 2, did anyone play that as well?

247
00:14:30,436 --> 00:14:32,577
Yeah, cool, good to hear.

248
00:14:33,611 --> 00:14:38,274
And the first thing that happened was that we got approached by a lot of fans, saying like,

249
00:14:38,434 --> 00:14:42,896
you have to do this, you have to do that, you have to do this. And this is like seven years ago,

250
00:14:42,976 --> 00:14:48,079
I think. And we said, you know what, we're great game designers, we can do whatever we want to do,

251
00:14:48,520 --> 00:14:52,482
so shut up and stay on the forums. And we did not communicate that well with the audience.

252
00:14:53,538 --> 00:14:57,481
So what happened was that, first of all, they made up a lot of conspiracy theories

253
00:14:57,541 --> 00:15:00,142
about what we were actually going to destroy in this game,

254
00:15:00,182 --> 00:15:04,525
because our intention, obviously, was to destroy the franchise when we bought it.

255
00:15:05,225 --> 00:15:07,147
Right? That's why you buy a franchise.

256
00:15:07,187 --> 00:15:08,447
It's to completely destroy it.

257
00:15:08,908 --> 00:15:11,849
Same thing happened with Star Wars and Disney, actually, when they're out like,

258
00:15:11,989 --> 00:15:13,430
oh, now they're going to destroy it.

259
00:15:13,450 --> 00:15:16,352
Yeah. If you put $7 billion into something,

260
00:15:16,412 --> 00:15:19,194
your first idea is obviously to flush it down the toilet.

261
00:15:19,454 --> 00:15:19,634
Right?

262
00:15:21,368 --> 00:15:25,550
The problem with that is that if you don't communicate with people like we did not do

263
00:15:26,010 --> 00:15:29,492
about that, they're going to be very conspirational.

264
00:15:29,672 --> 00:15:34,934
So they're going to come up with shit that you think is the JFK murder again.

265
00:15:36,034 --> 00:15:39,616
So what happened was that we released the game, the target audience was really pissed

266
00:15:39,696 --> 00:15:44,298
off because they said all the terrible things we just couldn't imagine how terrible they

267
00:15:44,338 --> 00:15:44,558
were.

268
00:15:44,638 --> 00:15:45,878
You actually implemented it.

269
00:15:46,198 --> 00:15:49,020
But it wasn't actually true because they thought a lot worse than that.

270
00:15:50,297 --> 00:15:56,019
But even worse was that every time a positive gamer came into our forums and said,

271
00:15:56,039 --> 00:15:59,080
you know what, I really like this game, but I got stuck at level 8.

272
00:16:00,000 --> 00:16:03,301
He was jumped by this crowd who just tore him apart and said,

273
00:16:03,521 --> 00:16:05,422
how can you like this game? It's shit!

274
00:16:07,243 --> 00:16:08,723
There you go. That's your demanding audience.

275
00:16:09,283 --> 00:16:15,626
Same thing is going to happen if you move into something that is, say, dungeon-keeper-esque.

276
00:16:16,206 --> 00:16:18,467
You just inherit the audience. Right?

277
00:16:19,598 --> 00:16:21,860
Now Dungeon Keeper is a bad example and you all know why.

278
00:16:25,122 --> 00:16:27,384
On the other hand, you can get away with cloning as well.

279
00:16:30,106 --> 00:16:34,790
Because the negative perception is much less in certain areas and we've seen this as well.

280
00:16:35,570 --> 00:16:37,892
First of all, low engagement target audiences.

281
00:16:37,912 --> 00:16:38,853
We're talking mobile.

282
00:16:39,213 --> 00:16:42,155
There's a reason why it works to steal other people's...

283
00:16:44,133 --> 00:16:46,555
names and steal other people's gaming concepts on mobile.

284
00:16:46,815 --> 00:16:47,936
Splashy Fish, for example.

285
00:16:48,456 --> 00:16:51,038
It's because people are not that engaged.

286
00:16:51,278 --> 00:16:54,420
There is no diehard fan of Flappy Birds.

287
00:16:55,081 --> 00:16:57,663
Who's going to write like 10 pages on a forum

288
00:16:57,783 --> 00:16:58,643
about Flappy Birds?

289
00:16:59,944 --> 00:17:01,606
Maybe a Flappy Birds convention, though.

290
00:17:02,026 --> 00:17:02,967
On the other hand, you never know.

291
00:17:03,907 --> 00:17:05,969
But when it comes to, for example, Minecraft,

292
00:17:06,069 --> 00:17:07,310
it's a totally different story.

293
00:17:09,591 --> 00:17:11,793
There's also something called underserved niches.

294
00:17:12,193 --> 00:17:12,994
Is this mic turned off?

295
00:17:15,305 --> 00:17:16,206
Nowadays, yeah, cool.

296
00:17:18,668 --> 00:17:20,790
And these are niches where people still

297
00:17:20,890 --> 00:17:22,431
are craving a lot of content.

298
00:17:23,372 --> 00:17:26,615
There are like, you can take for example,

299
00:17:27,155 --> 00:17:29,337
city building is a good example right now.

300
00:17:30,157 --> 00:17:32,259
Because you all know what happened to SimCity 5.

301
00:17:32,720 --> 00:17:35,402
If that had been a huge success, the market

302
00:17:35,422 --> 00:17:38,244
would have been totally taken by EA.

303
00:17:38,844 --> 00:17:40,246
Now the market is totally open.

304
00:17:41,126 --> 00:17:42,848
And we're getting back to SimCity 5 as well.

305
00:17:45,393 --> 00:17:49,535
I think another underserved niche are simulators in general.

306
00:17:49,736 --> 00:17:54,378
I would say that flight simulator is another niche that probably could be filled by this.

307
00:17:54,718 --> 00:17:59,340
It's a bit of a stretch budget-wise to make a flight simulator, but for anyone who could,

308
00:17:59,360 --> 00:18:03,822
you'll inherit a lot of bonus fans and you'll be alone in the market.

309
00:18:09,858 --> 00:18:13,060
My own guess is that space is the new thing.

310
00:18:13,560 --> 00:18:15,721
So if you want to release a space game,

311
00:18:15,921 --> 00:18:17,622
I think you should do it before 2016.

312
00:18:18,162 --> 00:18:21,064
Because I think the space is what people are doing right now.

313
00:18:21,124 --> 00:18:24,946
You know, black holes, and wormholes in space, and all that.

314
00:18:25,566 --> 00:18:25,706
Quack.

315
00:18:34,389 --> 00:18:39,074
I was talking about target audience and how to work with the target audience.

316
00:18:40,015 --> 00:18:45,221
The target audience that you inherit, I now assume that you make something that at least

317
00:18:45,301 --> 00:18:49,065
can be seen as something that is similar to something else.

318
00:18:50,366 --> 00:18:55,812
They will have very specific ideas of what you can do with your game.

319
00:18:56,903 --> 00:18:57,944
We know that at Paradox.

320
00:18:58,484 --> 00:19:00,585
When we started making Hearts of Iron 4,

321
00:19:01,366 --> 00:19:03,147
a lot of people, or if it was Hearts of Iron 3,

322
00:19:03,407 --> 00:19:05,128
I have one of the Hearts of Iron 4 developers here,

323
00:19:05,148 --> 00:19:06,849
so I'm not sure which game it actually was.

324
00:19:06,869 --> 00:19:08,169
It was in the Hearts of Iron series.

325
00:19:08,730 --> 00:19:10,310
We presented a new screenshot,

326
00:19:10,871 --> 00:19:13,232
and first comment was this, this is not Hearts of Iron.

327
00:19:13,852 --> 00:19:14,673
This is not hard to find.

328
00:19:14,953 --> 00:19:16,834
Like, make it the real game.

329
00:19:16,894 --> 00:19:19,095
Like, make it the game we actually own.

330
00:19:19,475 --> 00:19:23,377
So our fans have a very specific feeling

331
00:19:23,417 --> 00:19:26,119
that they own our franchises, which is a good thing.

332
00:19:26,319 --> 00:19:29,260
It makes them loyal, but it also puts a lot of pressure

333
00:19:29,340 --> 00:19:31,422
on us both to deliver and to communicate.

334
00:19:32,890 --> 00:19:35,591
They will have ideas about your game design.

335
00:19:36,171 --> 00:19:39,992
They will have ideas about how you conduct your business.

336
00:19:40,532 --> 00:19:44,133
They will have ideas about the price point, the DLC plan,

337
00:19:44,194 --> 00:19:47,534
how you patch the game, essentially everything.

338
00:19:50,535 --> 00:19:52,716
So how do you put all of this together,

339
00:19:53,116 --> 00:19:55,397
get the customers on your side, and work

340
00:19:55,577 --> 00:19:58,478
in a methodological way to actually stand out

341
00:19:58,518 --> 00:20:01,638
in the market, given the assumptions that we have here?

342
00:20:07,259 --> 00:20:09,621
First of all, I was not gonna touch that much

343
00:20:09,681 --> 00:20:13,624
on game design, but I'm gonna at least mention it

344
00:20:13,664 --> 00:20:15,146
because it's an important way.

345
00:20:15,186 --> 00:20:18,148
I'm gonna mention it from a methodological standpoint.

346
00:20:20,880 --> 00:20:24,543
Standing out basically is making people believe

347
00:20:24,963 --> 00:20:27,786
that you do things that no one has ever done before.

348
00:20:28,206 --> 00:20:31,128
And it can be done in a few different ways.

349
00:20:31,769 --> 00:20:34,711
This is actually how we do things at Paradox.

350
00:20:35,092 --> 00:20:37,494
We try to imagine what people are doing

351
00:20:37,754 --> 00:20:39,335
when they're not playing the game,

352
00:20:39,575 --> 00:20:41,077
just imagining the game.

353
00:20:41,917 --> 00:20:43,499
So of course, in game design,

354
00:20:43,539 --> 00:20:45,360
you can make your character stand out.

355
00:20:45,761 --> 00:20:47,062
We try to do that for every game.

356
00:20:47,742 --> 00:20:49,023
How many in here played Magicka?

357
00:20:52,979 --> 00:20:53,380
Quite a few.

358
00:20:53,800 --> 00:20:57,822
And how many would recognize a Magicka wizard if you saw one on the street?

359
00:20:59,442 --> 00:21:00,583
That's even more people.

360
00:21:00,803 --> 00:21:02,664
That's a good job from our marketing department.

361
00:21:03,504 --> 00:21:04,525
That kind of proves my point.

362
00:21:05,385 --> 00:21:11,868
If you see someone cosplaying as your game, what do they dress in then?

363
00:21:12,269 --> 00:21:16,050
My absolute favorite cosplay for me would be Super Meat Boy.

364
00:21:16,391 --> 00:21:19,112
I would love that costume, the full Super Meat Boy costume.

365
00:21:19,996 --> 00:21:24,377
I'm not going for the t-shirt here, because that's beautiful too, but the full Super Meat Boy outfit.

366
00:21:25,798 --> 00:21:26,658
That is really interesting.

367
00:21:26,678 --> 00:21:32,200
So the characters in your game, how do they stand out and how are they a character in

368
00:21:32,240 --> 00:21:32,620
itself?

369
00:21:32,680 --> 00:21:37,782
So when they walk on the street, people will recognize and say, wow, Magicka, or who?

370
00:21:38,002 --> 00:21:38,842
That's Gears of War.

371
00:21:39,502 --> 00:21:40,323
Very important.

372
00:21:41,743 --> 00:21:43,464
Same goes for art and level design.

373
00:21:43,484 --> 00:21:46,965
You should almost see on the colors that it's your game, obviously.

374
00:21:48,897 --> 00:21:50,937
On the marketing side, we released,

375
00:21:51,217 --> 00:21:55,099
that is also interesting to see that we invent characters

376
00:21:55,359 --> 00:21:59,440
not only in our games, but also in everything else we do,

377
00:21:59,560 --> 00:22:02,101
in the communication, in the trailers that we do,

378
00:22:02,521 --> 00:22:04,402
in everything that has to do with the game.

379
00:22:05,322 --> 00:22:08,243
How many saw the trailer for our game Leviathan Warships?

380
00:22:09,384 --> 00:22:09,624
Anyone?

381
00:22:09,924 --> 00:22:10,944
Yeah, quite a few.

382
00:22:11,704 --> 00:22:15,806
So that game, we invented a character called Jazz Boatman.

383
00:22:16,687 --> 00:22:21,810
This all goes back to that we had no really good budget to make a cool trailer,

384
00:22:22,270 --> 00:22:25,112
because it's a game about boats and explosions.

385
00:22:25,993 --> 00:22:29,936
So this guy talks in a smooth voice that sounds like Barry White,

386
00:22:30,236 --> 00:22:34,239
and he goes on for one and a half minutes explaining boats and making boat jokes,

387
00:22:34,399 --> 00:22:36,100
like ship just got real.

388
00:22:36,881 --> 00:22:38,542
So that trailer cost us, I think, $500 to make.

389
00:22:40,470 --> 00:22:43,933
And it got close to a million views now on YouTube.

390
00:22:44,554 --> 00:22:46,456
It's our most viewed trailer up to date.

391
00:22:47,375 --> 00:22:48,655
still our cheapest trailer as well,

392
00:22:49,055 --> 00:22:50,595
is because the groundwork that we did,

393
00:22:50,635 --> 00:22:52,736
like what is the character going to be,

394
00:22:53,076 --> 00:22:54,876
how is he going to be perceived by the market,

395
00:22:55,356 --> 00:22:57,317
what is the actual things we want to say

396
00:22:57,677 --> 00:22:59,737
only from this character, never mind the game.

397
00:23:00,057 --> 00:23:01,117
This is just the character.

398
00:23:01,137 --> 00:23:02,758
If he wants to describe this game,

399
00:23:03,278 --> 00:23:05,638
how would he do it from his couch position

400
00:23:06,038 --> 00:23:08,699
where he is Jassy Boatman playing the game

401
00:23:08,979 --> 00:23:11,500
but not being in the game, right?

402
00:23:12,680 --> 00:23:15,100
And these are the things that we look at on the side here.

403
00:23:16,188 --> 00:23:18,969
Play it, obviously the game in itself, when you play the game.

404
00:23:19,109 --> 00:23:19,530
What do you do?

405
00:23:20,270 --> 00:23:20,610
Read it.

406
00:23:20,970 --> 00:23:24,232
If your game was a book, what would the book be about?

407
00:23:24,833 --> 00:23:26,794
Would it be a funny book?

408
00:23:27,234 --> 00:23:28,354
Would it be sad?

409
00:23:28,895 --> 00:23:30,336
Would it be ironic?

410
00:23:31,116 --> 00:23:32,797
What would be the actual feeling?

411
00:23:32,817 --> 00:23:35,078
When you read this book and you're finished with the book,

412
00:23:35,759 --> 00:23:38,680
what does the reader take with them to the next book,

413
00:23:38,740 --> 00:23:40,061
to the sequel of this book?

414
00:23:41,895 --> 00:23:44,077
Wear it, like I was mentioning before.

415
00:23:44,718 --> 00:23:49,924
If you cosplay your game, what are you cosplaying the game like?

416
00:23:51,847 --> 00:23:54,550
I mentioned the Magicka Wizards, which is obviously for Magicka.

417
00:23:55,151 --> 00:23:56,532
For our historical games...

418
00:23:57,659 --> 00:23:58,560
It's much harder to say.

419
00:23:58,880 --> 00:24:01,101
Hearts of Iron is World War II, which is more generic.

420
00:24:01,582 --> 00:24:05,104
But instead, in Hearts of Iron, it's a very deep strategy game.

421
00:24:06,084 --> 00:24:08,126
And so you can't use Churchill, and you

422
00:24:08,166 --> 00:24:09,627
can't use these big leaders.

423
00:24:09,647 --> 00:24:13,469
So we use Douglas MacArthur as our main character.

424
00:24:14,270 --> 00:24:15,450
Very characteristic character.

425
00:24:15,590 --> 00:24:17,472
So if you want to cosplay Hearts of Iron,

426
00:24:18,072 --> 00:24:20,513
you'll probably go as Douglas MacArthur.

427
00:24:23,474 --> 00:24:24,014
Watch it.

428
00:24:24,715 --> 00:24:26,156
Same thing if your game was a movie.

429
00:24:26,456 --> 00:24:27,557
What would the movie be about?

430
00:24:27,877 --> 00:24:30,619
Who would be the lead actors in your movie?

431
00:24:32,080 --> 00:24:39,226
We think that Magicka would probably be Eddie Murphy playing the lead Red Wizard.

432
00:24:40,887 --> 00:24:41,307
Maybe not.

433
00:24:41,828 --> 00:24:42,148
We'll see.

434
00:24:42,328 --> 00:24:43,089
We'll see about that.

435
00:24:43,549 --> 00:24:44,530
Will Ferrell, maybe?

436
00:24:45,851 --> 00:24:46,171
We don't know.

437
00:24:47,468 --> 00:24:49,929
That is very interesting to say because once you sit down

438
00:24:50,049 --> 00:24:52,790
and you compare like, okay, so we're making a magic movie.

439
00:24:52,890 --> 00:24:53,990
Who's making the voices?

440
00:24:54,030 --> 00:24:56,191
Because you can't see the faces of the wizards.

441
00:24:56,471 --> 00:24:57,192
It's only the voices.

442
00:24:58,312 --> 00:24:58,932
Who's playing that?

443
00:24:59,373 --> 00:25:01,273
What personality does that give your game

444
00:25:01,674 --> 00:25:02,934
when you talk in between each other?

445
00:25:04,605 --> 00:25:07,666
So build it, how do you include your target audience?

446
00:25:08,006 --> 00:25:10,007
Modding is a big part of our community, for example,

447
00:25:10,107 --> 00:25:11,687
but it can be other things as well.

448
00:25:11,987 --> 00:25:14,648
If you welcome fan art, for example, for your project,

449
00:25:15,008 --> 00:25:16,288
what is that fan art going to be?

450
00:25:16,548 --> 00:25:19,609
How do you inspire people to make things for your game

451
00:25:19,969 --> 00:25:22,809
that people just feel that creativity flows through them?

452
00:25:25,210 --> 00:25:27,390
And preach it.

453
00:25:28,399 --> 00:25:29,060
Very important.

454
00:25:30,141 --> 00:25:32,363
What does other people say about your game

455
00:25:32,663 --> 00:25:34,004
when they talk to their friends?

456
00:25:34,905 --> 00:25:38,368
I know that we marketed our Europa Universalis series

457
00:25:38,669 --> 00:25:39,930
when we released the third one.

458
00:25:40,110 --> 00:25:40,590
Just a second.

459
00:25:44,474 --> 00:25:46,516
As we said to people like this,

460
00:25:47,617 --> 00:25:50,900
maybe this game is a little bit too hard for you.

461
00:25:51,861 --> 00:25:52,581
So people were like, what?

462
00:25:54,070 --> 00:25:56,031
Yeah, we said this game might be a bit too hard.

463
00:25:56,071 --> 00:25:58,513
It's a very, very advanced strategy.

464
00:25:58,973 --> 00:26:00,674
Yeah, OK, I have to check that out.

465
00:26:01,434 --> 00:26:03,115
So it was a form of anti-marketing.

466
00:26:03,175 --> 00:26:05,717
So we were not pushing things in people's faces.

467
00:26:06,337 --> 00:26:10,539
But we said, when you tell your friends about Europa

468
00:26:10,559 --> 00:26:12,020
Universalis, it's going to be, you know what?

469
00:26:12,080 --> 00:26:13,181
I'm playing this awesome game.

470
00:26:13,801 --> 00:26:16,703
But you probably don't understand how to play it,

471
00:26:16,763 --> 00:26:17,743
because it's very advanced.

472
00:26:18,744 --> 00:26:21,365
So that's how we spread the word on our strategy games.

473
00:26:22,117 --> 00:26:24,338
from a communication standpoint when it comes to peer-to-peer.

474
00:26:26,739 --> 00:26:29,800
And this one, this sounds almost like we're being a sect here,

475
00:26:29,960 --> 00:26:33,942
which is kind of awesome in itself, but live it.

476
00:26:35,022 --> 00:26:39,804
When this game embraces your entire life,

477
00:26:40,285 --> 00:26:42,906
and you do nothing else than live

478
00:26:43,166 --> 00:26:47,048
within this gaming community, gaming franchise,

479
00:26:47,808 --> 00:26:49,789
what does your everyday life look like?

480
00:26:50,969 --> 00:26:51,870
You just try to imagine.

481
00:26:54,672 --> 00:26:57,512
I have to get back to Super Meat Boy and do all of this, I feel that.

482
00:26:58,953 --> 00:27:03,114
So this is how we do things in Paradox, when we try to think outside the game, seeing like,

483
00:27:03,174 --> 00:27:08,896
okay, we have the game, but everything else around that, how are we going to make it stand

484
00:27:09,036 --> 00:27:13,777
out so that everyone, when they see it, like, bam, there it is, that's the game.

485
00:27:15,218 --> 00:27:16,098
Giving it personality.

486
00:27:24,929 --> 00:27:27,872
Standing out as well is obviously, like I said,

487
00:27:27,912 --> 00:27:29,053
not only the games in itself,

488
00:27:29,073 --> 00:27:30,455
but also the business that you do.

489
00:27:31,917 --> 00:27:33,839
How do you update what you're doing?

490
00:27:35,080 --> 00:27:37,063
What is your DLC policy like?

491
00:27:37,603 --> 00:27:39,025
What is your patching policy?

