16, okay, I'll speed this up.

747
00:41:19,992 --> 00:41:20,512
Getting started.

748
00:41:20,532 --> 00:41:23,274
The most important thing that we said,

749
00:41:23,815 --> 00:41:24,835
I was touching on this a bit,

750
00:41:24,896 --> 00:41:27,097
with read it, play it, watch it, wear it, et cetera,

751
00:41:27,318 --> 00:41:29,619
is setting the product vision.

752
00:41:29,800 --> 00:41:31,401
And why do you set a product vision?

753
00:41:32,907 --> 00:41:37,069
It's to get all the major influencers in the company looking at the same target goal.

754
00:41:37,389 --> 00:41:44,773
It's also a good way to communicate externally what you're trying to achieve with the game.

755
00:41:45,914 --> 00:41:50,316
An example of...

756
00:41:50,396 --> 00:41:56,260
There are no examples of games being shipped that are not teamwork in this industry.

757
00:41:56,700 --> 00:41:59,822
With one example, and that's Minecraft, which is probably one man's work.

758
00:42:04,204 --> 00:42:11,189
A good vision can summarize the feeling when you play the game and make everyone understand

759
00:42:11,229 --> 00:42:12,050
what you're trying to achieve.

760
00:42:12,090 --> 00:42:17,154
A good vision you can look at every day and say, my daily work is being done.

761
00:42:18,299 --> 00:42:22,481
And I'm following the vision that is our overall goal with this product.

762
00:42:23,241 --> 00:42:26,162
One such example is actually SimCity, which is saying,

763
00:42:26,222 --> 00:42:27,563
build the city of your dreams.

764
00:42:28,043 --> 00:42:28,883
That's a really good vision.

765
00:42:29,243 --> 00:42:32,344
It's really simple to understand, good tagline.

766
00:42:32,965 --> 00:42:36,606
For Europa Universalis, we've used, be a Renaissance emperor.

767
00:42:37,747 --> 00:42:38,727
Very easy to understand.

768
00:42:38,767 --> 00:42:40,207
What kind of decisions are you making?

769
00:42:40,267 --> 00:42:41,168
How do you play the game?

770
00:42:41,228 --> 00:42:42,688
How do you feel when you play the game?

771
00:42:44,868 --> 00:42:50,032
Gears of War allegedly, I'm not sure if this is true, but if I understand correctly,

772
00:42:50,092 --> 00:42:54,736
they used an even more down-to-earth vision when they created their game.

773
00:42:55,137 --> 00:42:58,079
They said Marcus Fenix is a total badass.

774
00:42:59,460 --> 00:43:00,321
And how is that a vision?

775
00:43:00,902 --> 00:43:03,284
Well, everything he does is badass.

776
00:43:04,325 --> 00:43:05,786
He doesn't open doors, right?

777
00:43:06,166 --> 00:43:07,487
He kicks doors in.

778
00:43:08,308 --> 00:43:08,909
That's badass.

779
00:43:08,949 --> 00:43:10,930
You don't open the door like this, you just BAM!

780
00:43:11,973 --> 00:43:16,234
So if you're a designer and you see that vision, Marcus Phoenix is a badass.

781
00:43:16,554 --> 00:43:17,495
How does he behave?

782
00:43:17,735 --> 00:43:19,295
How does that affect the gameplay?

783
00:43:19,595 --> 00:43:21,496
How does that affect marketing in the game?

784
00:43:22,356 --> 00:43:28,777
Examples of really bad visions is, we're going to make the best strategy game in the world.

785
00:43:30,417 --> 00:43:31,558
And why is that a bad vision?

786
00:43:32,198 --> 00:43:34,718
Because best is a very subjective matter.

787
00:43:36,122 --> 00:43:42,103
No one can look at that and say, okay, so, hmm, is this real-time or turn-based?

788
00:43:42,583 --> 00:43:43,824
It doesn't make sense at all.

789
00:43:47,024 --> 00:43:49,464
So the vision should be simple for everyone on the team to understand.

790
00:43:49,805 --> 00:43:51,265
I said use yourself as benchmark.

791
00:43:51,365 --> 00:43:59,266
And the be crazy part I just added because as I say, what you like and you're trying

792
00:43:59,306 --> 00:44:04,127
to sell, if you twist it around a bit, other people are going to like that too because

793
00:44:04,167 --> 00:44:05,127
that's how the market works.

794
00:44:10,071 --> 00:44:16,854
You take the vision, you boil it down, you sell the idea internally when all the stakeholders are on board with this vision.

795
00:44:17,314 --> 00:44:22,737
Typically, you have to sit down in a locked room until you come up with your product vision.

796
00:44:22,897 --> 00:44:29,821
There are many ways to do this. I could have one session only on how to set the product vision,

797
00:44:30,421 --> 00:44:32,462
because that takes probably a few hours to explain.

798
00:44:32,942 --> 00:44:35,463
But lock people in a room, maybe a few beers.

799
00:44:36,942 --> 00:44:42,467
and then you don't walk out until all the major stakeholders are on board on the same page.

800
00:44:42,847 --> 00:44:48,071
You can then take the vision and say, okay, you're in charge of programming.

801
00:44:48,852 --> 00:44:54,697
What do you do to fulfill the vision in your daily work? Five tasks in your daily work.

802
00:44:55,557 --> 00:45:00,922
You're the lead artist. How do you make sure that this vision is followed on a daily basis?

803
00:45:01,502 --> 00:45:02,183
These five

804
00:45:03,092 --> 00:45:04,773
bullet points or three bullet points,

805
00:45:05,073 --> 00:45:07,094
you can take back to your team and say,

806
00:45:07,735 --> 00:45:09,876
this is how we work to fulfill our mission.

807
00:45:10,376 --> 00:45:11,336
This is the grand vision.

808
00:45:11,697 --> 00:45:14,818
This is what we do to fulfill our part of this grand vision.

809
00:45:15,479 --> 00:45:18,000
Makes it so much easier for people to understand

810
00:45:18,340 --> 00:45:19,801
both internally and externally.

811
00:45:21,776 --> 00:45:26,978
It's super good for communication as well because it sets the whole pace for trailers that you're making,

812
00:45:27,258 --> 00:45:28,839
for communications that you're making.

813
00:45:29,559 --> 00:45:31,580
Magicka is a perfect example of everything.

814
00:45:32,160 --> 00:45:38,522
Everything in Magicka, every single line that someone says is a reference to popular culture.

815
00:45:39,082 --> 00:45:39,863
Everything in the game.

816
00:45:40,603 --> 00:45:45,385
That includes all the trailers, it includes all the achievements, it includes everything.

817
00:45:46,279 --> 00:45:53,127
I only get about 33% of that, but when I sometimes get it, I really find it, I really love.

818
00:45:53,147 --> 00:45:55,930
I was standing next to this...

819
00:45:57,983 --> 00:46:03,347
building called Graham's Workshop, which looks a bit like Games Workshop in the logotype,

820
00:46:03,367 --> 00:46:09,972
because it's yellow and red. And the guy next to Graham's Workshop says, when I click a dialogue,

821
00:46:10,012 --> 00:46:16,257
he says, someone at Graham's Workshop told me that in a distant future there is only war.

822
00:46:16,877 --> 00:46:19,859
I find that kind of scary. And I started laughing.

823
00:46:22,021 --> 00:46:26,324
No one? Okay, we'll take that later. Write that down and we'll take it later.

824
00:46:27,339 --> 00:46:29,660
It's also important that you keep the vision true as a team.

825
00:46:29,700 --> 00:46:30,760
You challenge each other.

826
00:46:31,061 --> 00:46:33,102
You go up to, even if you're not an artist,

827
00:46:33,122 --> 00:46:34,602
you can go up and say, you know what?

828
00:46:35,503 --> 00:46:37,224
How is this badass?

829
00:46:37,584 --> 00:46:39,225
How is this art actually badass?

830
00:46:39,325 --> 00:46:41,346
Is this something that we want to stand for

831
00:46:41,546 --> 00:46:43,828
and we want to be behind when we release the game

832
00:46:44,068 --> 00:46:46,429
with a vision we already agreed up?

833
00:46:48,450 --> 00:46:50,031
Another thing that I think is underestimated,

834
00:46:50,051 --> 00:46:51,352
I'm going to hurry up a bit here,

835
00:46:51,492 --> 00:46:53,493
it's naming the game.

836
00:46:53,793 --> 00:46:55,354
Just such a simple thing because

837
00:46:56,477 --> 00:46:57,658
Naming a game takes forever.

838
00:46:57,698 --> 00:47:00,700
First of all, you have to search all the trademark databases and all that,

839
00:47:00,720 --> 00:47:04,823
and then you have to figure if your name is a funny meaning in a foreign language.

840
00:47:05,163 --> 00:47:06,684
And yeah, there are so many things.

841
00:47:07,865 --> 00:47:08,465
Keep it simple.

842
00:47:10,546 --> 00:47:13,008
I love the old ADOS way of naming games.

843
00:47:13,408 --> 00:47:14,369
You are what you play.

844
00:47:14,689 --> 00:47:19,352
They did Hitman, Championship Manager, Thief.

845
00:47:20,413 --> 00:47:20,953
Super simple.

846
00:47:21,917 --> 00:47:27,821
The only downside is that it's not Googleable in the same way that a very strange name like Europa Universal is.

847
00:47:27,861 --> 00:47:30,182
If you Google that, you'll only get hit some paradox.

848
00:47:31,744 --> 00:47:32,744
There are downsides to everything.

849
00:47:36,527 --> 00:47:39,249
From the vision, we boil it down to a consumer promise as well.

850
00:47:39,469 --> 00:47:43,092
Like, what is the package that we promise to deliver to a consumer?

851
00:47:43,492 --> 00:47:48,215
So what we do is ask ourselves, through the communication that we've done,

852
00:47:48,496 --> 00:47:49,636
what are all the vision...

853
00:47:50,633 --> 00:47:53,715
things that we communicated out to the customers,

854
00:47:55,435 --> 00:47:56,776
everything communication-wise.

