00:55:38,255 --> 00:55:40,116
What legends do they tell about you?

981
00:55:40,536 --> 00:55:44,078
How good are you as a storyteller about your company?

982
00:55:44,098 --> 00:55:47,640
Because the company standing out is just as important

983
00:55:48,100 --> 00:55:49,500
as the game standing out in itself.

984
00:55:49,981 --> 00:55:51,401
Because a standout company

985
00:55:52,243 --> 00:55:55,485
can release mediocre games and get away with it,

986
00:55:55,845 --> 00:55:57,646
because they're a standout company.

987
00:55:58,446 --> 00:55:59,887
I'm not going to take any examples here,

988
00:56:00,307 --> 00:56:02,108
but it's very interesting.

989
00:56:02,449 --> 00:56:05,970
So how, in essence, do you create the sense of belonging

990
00:56:06,191 --> 00:56:07,791
that you want for your gamers,

991
00:56:08,292 --> 00:56:15,416
that they belong to what you're doing?

992
00:56:15,436 --> 00:56:17,637
So if I'm going to summarize what I've said here,

993
00:56:18,137 --> 00:56:20,999
divide it up to product, company,

994
00:56:23,251 --> 00:56:28,234
We say in Paradox that passion makes perfect, meaning that passion is more important than

995
00:56:28,314 --> 00:56:28,874
strategy.

996
00:56:30,475 --> 00:56:33,797
Passion is more important than everything you do in the game, because it means that

997
00:56:33,837 --> 00:56:37,500
you're willing to work hard to succeed and to complete what you're doing.

998
00:56:38,500 --> 00:56:44,884
First of all, if I'm just going to make, set some advices here, is to set your vision and

999
00:56:44,924 --> 00:56:46,245
get your team on board with that.

1000
00:56:49,972 --> 00:56:54,613
Make sure to communicate what your vision and your consumer promise is to the people

1001
00:56:54,653 --> 00:56:56,874
are supposed to play your games.

1002
00:56:59,294 --> 00:57:04,235
And be passionate and follow your heart when it comes to everything, not only to the game,

1003
00:57:04,816 --> 00:57:07,376
but to the marketing and to the business of the game.

1004
00:57:09,677 --> 00:57:10,017
That's all.

1005
00:57:11,677 --> 00:57:11,877
Thank you.

1006
00:57:20,364 --> 00:57:21,705
So now I've been talking for an hour.

1007
00:57:21,725 --> 00:57:22,586
Any questions?

1008
00:57:23,987 --> 00:57:24,227
Yes?

1009
00:57:24,487 --> 00:57:26,408
Microphone here, if you can use it please.

1010
00:57:30,732 --> 00:57:33,894
Hello, I have a question about your internal methods

1011
00:57:34,034 --> 00:57:35,895
and being brutally honest to yourselves.

1012
00:57:36,295 --> 00:57:36,996
Yep.

1013
00:57:37,116 --> 00:57:39,798
What do you do if someone on the development team

1014
00:57:39,878 --> 00:57:42,720
loses his passion during the game they're working on

1015
00:57:42,840 --> 00:57:43,961
and how do you proceed with this?

1016
00:57:44,942 --> 00:57:45,882
That's a very good question.

1017
00:57:45,942 --> 00:57:47,383
How do we get the passion going?

1018
00:57:48,677 --> 00:57:53,019
When we have introduction days at Paradox, we have one full day, that's how we start at least.

1019
00:57:53,859 --> 00:57:55,319
We have one full day of presentations.

1020
00:57:55,739 --> 00:58:00,701
I always start in the morning telling Paradox history, the organization, a lot of boring things.

1021
00:58:01,381 --> 00:58:04,822
I always end my presentations with saying, you know what,

1022
00:58:05,903 --> 00:58:09,204
when you walk into this office two weeks in a row or so,

1023
00:58:09,564 --> 00:58:12,765
and you don't feel that you're having fun, come to me.

1024
00:58:13,467 --> 00:58:16,288
Come to me, and I'll help you get a better job

1025
00:58:16,568 --> 00:58:18,288
than the job that you have here at Paradox.

1026
00:58:18,789 --> 00:58:19,129
I swear.

1027
00:58:20,349 --> 00:58:22,230
So that's how we start, like setting it straight,

1028
00:58:22,270 --> 00:58:25,731
saying like, it's mandatory to have fun at Paradox.

1029
00:58:26,171 --> 00:58:27,472
Nothing else actually counts.

1030
00:58:28,072 --> 00:58:29,672
But keeping the passion in the team

1031
00:58:29,792 --> 00:58:31,273
is actually something ongoing.

1032
00:58:31,453 --> 00:58:34,434
That is more like you try to have peer-to-peer evaluations

1033
00:58:34,454 --> 00:58:37,195
and all of that, but it's very hard and very tricky to do.

1034
00:58:37,415 --> 00:58:39,196
So I don't really have a straight answer on that.

1035
00:58:40,216 --> 00:58:40,876
Thank you very much.

1036
00:58:40,916 --> 00:58:41,117
Thank you.

1037
00:58:49,677 --> 00:58:58,199
The target group of some video game genres, especially war games, is pretty hardcore and traditional,

1038
00:58:58,419 --> 00:59:03,320
and they like certain aspects of gameplay that are recurring through the series.

1039
00:59:04,981 --> 00:59:10,202
So how do you balance innovations in game and also stay true to your fanbase

1040
00:59:10,522 --> 00:59:13,363
and make the games that they are used to and love?

1041
00:59:14,897 --> 00:59:19,008
How we stand true to the brand and at the same time try to make new things.

1042
00:59:22,947 --> 00:59:24,268
A lot of the, if you take war games,

1043
00:59:24,448 --> 00:59:27,868
or for example, Hearts of Iron as an example of that,

1044
00:59:27,888 --> 00:59:31,589
I think that we have hidden a lot of what is actually fun

1045
00:59:31,749 --> 00:59:34,330
in the game underneath the surface in the past.

1046
00:59:34,390 --> 00:59:36,870
I think that probably everyone in the world

1047
00:59:36,970 --> 00:59:38,571
can enjoy a good war game,

1048
00:59:38,851 --> 00:59:41,571
because it's like the basis of what you play,

1049
00:59:41,692 --> 00:59:42,732
even now today.

1050
00:59:43,072 --> 00:59:45,252
War games are the foundation of a lot of games.

1051
00:59:45,712 --> 00:59:48,833
So in our case, I think one of the challenges,

1052
00:59:48,893 --> 00:59:50,333
we have one of the Hearts of Iron developers here,

1053
00:59:50,353 --> 00:59:51,414
so you can talk to him later on.

1054
00:59:51,794 --> 00:59:52,294
Hand up here.

1055
00:59:52,314 --> 00:59:52,774
Ha ha.

1056
00:59:53,614 --> 00:59:59,275
I think one of the challenges that we have is trying to lift it up to the surface and telling people like this is

1057
00:59:59,435 --> 01:00:04,056
Actually, what is fun in this game? And this is how you learn it. So it's it's a lot of

1058
01:00:04,297 --> 01:00:10,458
Interface issues actually, so it's very technical what is fun in the game, but also on our end to communicate

1059
01:00:10,978 --> 01:00:15,179
This is what you can do in the game. This is the feeling you should have when you're playing the game so

1060
01:00:16,019 --> 01:00:18,504
It's both, a bit like lifting up what's fun

1061
01:00:19,065 --> 01:00:20,307
and the other one is communicating.

1062
01:00:20,547 --> 01:00:21,750
It's not just a war game,

1063
01:00:21,790 --> 01:00:25,837
it's like you're ruling the world, sort of, that feeling.

1064
01:00:25,857 --> 01:00:27,259
So a little bit of everything.

1065
01:00:27,600 --> 01:00:28,622
We have one more question.

1066
01:00:29,303 --> 01:00:29,443
Yep.

1067
01:00:32,517 --> 01:00:39,302
Hi, you've been talking about that you do have, you need your developers to have passion

1068
01:00:39,322 --> 01:00:41,924
for the game when they do the game and that they love to play the game.

1069
01:00:42,565 --> 01:00:46,288
You were also talking about that you need to listen to your customers and that your

1070
01:00:46,328 --> 01:00:51,672
customers are satisfied and that they are incorporated into the process in some way.

1071
01:00:51,692 --> 01:00:53,854
Do you ever have the situation that...

1072
01:00:54,994 --> 01:00:56,537
You're the developers and your customers

1073
01:00:57,017 --> 01:00:58,660
were drifting apart in their vision,

1074
01:00:59,080 --> 01:00:59,942
and how do you handle that?

1075
01:01:00,002 --> 01:01:02,405
I mean, if the team has an idea about where they want to go,

1076
01:01:02,786 --> 01:01:04,428
and it's totally not what the customers want,

1077
01:01:04,809 --> 01:01:05,390
what do you do then?

1078
01:01:05,750 --> 01:01:06,772
Well, we have that all the time.

1079
01:01:07,714 --> 01:01:12,277
Actually, and there are several ways to get people on board,

1080
01:01:12,598 --> 01:01:15,100
get the customers on board at an early stage.

1081
01:01:15,660 --> 01:01:18,943
What our strategy game teams are doing really well

1082
01:01:19,203 --> 01:01:20,925
is to release developer diaries,

1083
01:01:21,085 --> 01:01:23,407
where you explain bits of gameplay,

1084
01:01:23,567 --> 01:01:25,729
like every week you explain new things to the gameplay,

1085
01:01:26,029 --> 01:01:27,670
because that gets more and more people on board.

1086
01:01:27,690 --> 01:01:29,772
They're like, oh yeah, this sounds really smart,

1087
01:01:29,792 --> 01:01:31,814
and then you're very active in communication.

1088
01:01:32,976 --> 01:01:37,397
And you can also be like, you can listen to the fans, but you should also be very, very...

1089
01:01:39,455 --> 01:01:42,717
clear what they can say about the game,

1090
01:01:42,917 --> 01:01:45,197
saying like, you know what, we're hearing what you're saying

1091
01:01:45,237 --> 01:01:46,618
but this is how it will be.

1092
01:01:47,178 --> 01:01:48,919
So you're not fooling people to believe

1093
01:01:48,959 --> 01:01:52,140
that they have influence over something that they won't.

1094
01:01:52,700 --> 01:01:54,121
And then people can choose either to say,

1095
01:01:54,141 --> 01:01:57,562
okay, that's sad, but probably I'll play the game again,

1096
01:01:57,762 --> 01:02:00,063
or they'll be really happy about that.

1097
01:02:00,163 --> 01:02:02,664
So it's typically a dual situation.

1098
01:02:02,744 --> 01:02:04,865
But sometimes, in the past at least,

1099
01:02:05,065 --> 01:02:07,145
we did polls on the forums as well.

1100
01:02:07,165 --> 01:02:08,246
So we asked people like.

1101
01:02:09,517 --> 01:02:11,918
Do you want Paradox to do this next?

1102
01:02:12,619 --> 01:02:14,960
And then we had like, yes, because I love games,

1103
01:02:15,340 --> 01:02:17,461
or no, because I'm a boring person.

1104
01:02:18,101 --> 01:02:19,362
And then we got like 97% yes.

1105
01:02:19,402 --> 01:02:22,303
So it depends on how you ask the question as well.

1106
01:02:22,844 --> 01:02:24,264
It was not that obvious though,

1107
01:02:24,344 --> 01:02:26,705
but it depends a lot, like if you want people

1108
01:02:26,926 --> 01:02:29,327
to like really be on your side,

1109
01:02:29,487 --> 01:02:31,348
it depends a lot on how you ask the questions.

1110
01:02:36,402 --> 01:02:37,843
Oh, is that microphone not working?

1111
01:02:37,863 --> 01:02:38,323
No, working?

1112
01:02:38,783 --> 01:02:40,404
We've got one last question here.

1113
01:02:40,944 --> 01:02:42,765
Cool.

1114
01:02:43,646 --> 01:02:43,806
Hi.

1115
01:02:44,026 --> 01:02:50,449
How important do you think language localization is to engage people?

1116
01:02:52,325 --> 01:02:55,526
I think language localization is quite important,

1117
01:02:56,466 --> 01:03:00,127
especially since there are basically just a few territories

1118
01:03:00,167 --> 01:03:01,527
where you can release English games.

1119
01:03:01,607 --> 01:03:04,668
It's North America, it's UK, Netherlands,

1120
01:03:04,948 --> 01:03:05,808
Nordic territories.

1121
01:03:06,208 --> 01:03:07,549
Apart from that, if you want to reach

1122
01:03:07,569 --> 01:03:08,689
the highest sales numbers,

1123
01:03:08,729 --> 01:03:10,530
I think localization is very important.

1124
01:03:11,788 --> 01:03:13,329
And for us it's always a balance

1125
01:03:13,349 --> 01:03:14,530
in between localize or not.

1126
01:03:15,291 --> 01:03:17,192
Because if you take for example Europa Universalis,

1127
01:03:17,252 --> 01:03:19,054
it's like 600,000 words or something

1128
01:03:19,074 --> 01:03:20,215
in Europa Universalis for it.

1129
01:03:20,555 --> 01:03:21,396
So it's always a stretch.

1130
01:03:21,416 --> 01:03:24,178
But I think as a concept, localization is really important

1131
01:03:24,378 --> 01:03:26,059
to get into every local market.

1132
01:03:26,400 --> 01:03:28,642
Now that you have digital distribution

1133
01:03:28,862 --> 01:03:31,664
as like a global support on almost all platforms.

1134
01:03:37,409 --> 01:03:38,169
Okay, thank you.

1135
01:03:38,710 --> 01:03:39,070
Thank you.

1136
01:03:50,718 --> 01:03:50,778
you

